 Are you OK?

274
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:06,984
Looks like you've been crying.

275
00:13:06,984 --> 00:13:09,920
 Um, I lost a friend a few days ago.

276
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:12,200
And I just need to drive and be alone for a while.

277
00:13:12,200 --> 00:13:13,880
I'll be home soon.

278
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:15,270
 What's that in the back?

279
00:13:15,270 --> 00:13:16,280
 In the back? OFFICER: Mm.

280
00:13:16,280 --> 00:13:17,380
 Is there something in the back?

281
00:13:17,380 --> 00:13:18,616
Oh, that.

282
00:13:18,616 --> 00:13:24,285
That's, um, a big thing for my husband's birthday.

283
00:13:24,285 --> 00:13:25,740
OFFICER: Drive safe.

284
00:13:25,740 --> 00:13:27,195
Buckle up.

285
00:13:27,195 --> 00:13:30,105
[CAR ENGINE STARTS]

286
00:13:31,075 --> 00:13:34,060
WALTER: The gun's still aimed at you, lady.

287
00:13:34,060 --> 00:13:37,520
Just keep driving and don't look back.

288
00:13:37,520 --> 00:13:40,890
You sure could use some lying lessons.

289
00:13:40,890 --> 00:13:41,830
 [CRYING]

290
00:13:41,830 --> 00:13:44,627
WALTER: Now what's the matter?

291
00:13:44,627 --> 00:13:47,022
 It's my birthday today.

292
00:13:47,022 --> 00:13:52,291
[SOBS]

293
00:13:52,291 --> 00:13:54,200
 She'll be home, Mr. Brown.

294
00:13:54,200 --> 00:13:56,330
Said she needed to be alone for a while.

295
00:13:56,330 --> 00:13:57,500
 Is she OK?

296
00:13:57,500 --> 00:13:59,750
 She looked pretty upset, that she'd been crying.

297
00:13:59,750 --> 00:14:01,370
Uh, but she drove steady.

298
00:14:01,370 --> 00:14:02,930
I followed her for about a mile or two.

299
00:14:02,930 --> 00:14:04,760
 Why would you just ditch me at the mall?

300
00:14:04,760 --> 00:14:06,410
Something's wrong, Daddy.

301
00:14:06,410 --> 00:14:08,510
 You want to go look for her?

302
00:14:08,510 --> 00:14:10,790
Can I at least order some pizza then?

303
00:14:10,790 --> 00:14:13,073
 Oh, by the way, happy birthday, Mr. Brown.

304
00:14:13,073 --> 00:14:15,140
 But who told you it was my birthday?

305
00:14:15,140 --> 00:14:16,400
 Oh, she did.

306
00:14:16,400 --> 00:14:17,390
 What could she be thinking?

307
00:14:17,390 --> 00:14:20,370
My birthday isn't until next--

308
00:14:20,370 --> 00:14:21,270
oh.

309
00:14:21,270 --> 00:14:23,264
What's the date today?

310
00:14:23,264 --> 00:14:25,132
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

311
00:14:25,132 --> 00:14:26,069
WALTER: You all right?

312
00:14:26,340 --> 00:14:27,240
 No, I'm not all right.

313
00:14:27,240 --> 00:14:28,790
What are you going to do with me?

314
00:14:28,790 --> 00:14:31,100
I have a right to know.

315
00:14:31,100 --> 00:14:34,033
 Yeah, well, Jane, I've never been much at planning.

316
00:14:34,033 --> 00:14:35,845
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

317
00:14:35,845 --> 00:14:37,330
Oh, god, I hate lightning.

318
00:14:37,330 --> 00:14:39,040
Gives me the willies.

319
00:14:39,040 --> 00:14:40,465
Does it bother you?

320
00:14:40,465 --> 00:14:41,365
 No.

321
00:14:41,365 --> 00:14:43,410
 That's because you've never been hit by it.

322
00:14:43,410 --> 00:14:44,340
I have.

323
00:14:44,340 --> 00:14:47,120
Burned every last bit of body hair off me.

324
00:14:47,120 --> 00:14:48,120
Boy, was I ever funny looking.

325
00:14:51,978 --> 00:14:54,830
[BAG RUSTLING] Look at all this good stuff.

326
00:14:54,830 --> 00:14:56,740
We can get by for a week.

327
00:14:56,740 --> 00:14:59,930
 I have a daughter getting married on Saturday.

328
00:14:59,930 --> 00:15:01,430
They need me.

329
00:15:01,430 --> 00:15:02,620
 Oh they're big kids, huh?

330
00:15:02,620 --> 00:15:04,894
Come on, eat some.

331
00:15:04,894 --> 00:15:06,660
Boy, I wish you were having more fun.

332
00:15:06,660 --> 00:15:07,660
 Well, I'm not.

333
00:15:10,320 --> 00:15:12,900
 I'd like to stop for a drink, but I can't because I don't

334
00:15:12,900 --> 00:15:14,410
know what I'd do with you.

335
00:15:14,410 --> 00:15:17,466
So we got a lot of problems to work out, don't we?

336
00:15:17,466 --> 00:15:18,858
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

337
00:15:18,858 --> 00:15:22,134
 There's-- there's beer in that bag in the back.

338
00:15:22,134 --> 00:15:23,580
 What?

339
00:15:23,580 --> 00:15:26,886
Well, now we're going off on the right foot, aren't we?

340
00:15:26,886 --> 00:15:29,760
[BAG RUSTLING]

341
00:15:33,171 --> 00:15:34,071
WALTER: [INAUDIBLE]

342
00:15:34,071 --> 00:15:34,971
BUNNY: Oh!

343
00:15:34,971 --> 00:15:37,780
 [CHUCKLING] I'm too fast for you, Bunny.

344
00:15:37,780 --> 00:15:39,430
I can't trust you.

345
00:15:39,430 --> 00:15:40,600
That's too bad.

346
00:15:40,600 --> 00:15:42,930
Things would be better if I could.

347
00:15:42,930 --> 00:15:44,840
 Nothing would be better.

348
00:15:44,840 --> 00:15:46,320
What do you want, my body?

349
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:48,361
Would you let me go then?

350
00:15:48,361 --> 00:15:51,645
 You think I'm sick?

351
00:15:51,645 --> 00:15:54,460
Jeez Louise, what do you take me for?

352
00:15:54,460 --> 00:15:57,840
 A kidnapper and a bank robber, that's what.

353
00:15:57,840 --> 00:16:01,886
 Yeah, well, I bet you're not perfect either.

354
00:16:01,886 --> 00:16:04,790
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

355
00:16:04,790 --> 00:16:05,897
BUNNY: Where are we now?

356
00:16:05,897 --> 00:16:06,830
WALTER: This is my hometown.

357
00:16:06,830 --> 00:16:08,620
Got a nice feel to it, doesn't it?

358
00:16:08,620 --> 00:16:10,990
BUNNY: Not particularly.

359
00:16:10,990 --> 00:16:15,680
WALTER: Well, anyway, pull into that driveway right there.

360
00:16:15,680 --> 00:16:17,600
They'll be looking for this car.

361
00:16:17,600 --> 00:16:18,740
Pull it right up there and stop.

362
00:16:27,150 --> 00:16:28,050
All right, pull it in.

363
00:16:28,050 --> 00:16:30,330
They won't find it here in a million years.

364
00:16:37,190 --> 00:16:39,640
[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

365
00:16:40,620 --> 00:16:41,600
[INAUDIBLE]

366
00:16:46,990 --> 00:16:52,340
This, a '77 Monte Carlo, a classic.

367
00:16:52,340 --> 00:16:53,330
[INAUDIBLE]

368
00:16:58,280 --> 00:16:59,840
 What is this place?

369
00:16:59,840 --> 00:17:01,531
 Just mind your own business.

370
00:17:01,531 --> 00:17:03,836
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

371
00:17:04,758 --> 00:17:05,680
BUNNY: Ah!

372
00:17:05,680 --> 00:17:07,200
 [TSKING] Really, Walter.

373
00:17:07,200 --> 00:17:09,150
For a ladies man, you're slipping.

374
00:17:09,150 --> 00:17:10,450
 Oh, you leave her alone, Sebastian.

375
00:17:10,450 --> 00:17:11,579
She's got nothing to do with it.

376
00:17:11,579 --> 00:17:14,130
 Nice outfit, ma'am.

377
00:17:14,130 --> 00:17:17,280
 Well, Mr. Sharphorn, Walter, my friend.

378
00:17:17,280 --> 00:17:18,380
You're a day late, but you better

379
00:17:18,380 --> 00:17:19,647
not be even a dollar short.

380
00:17:19,647 --> 00:17:21,480
 Hey, look, that's what I wanted to talk to you about.

381
00:17:21,480 --> 00:17:22,879
 I'm already uncomfortable with the sound

382
00:17:22,879 --> 00:17:23,954
of your voice, Walter.

383
00:17:23,954 --> 00:17:26,520
 [LAUGHS] Look, I just need a couple more days.

384
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:28,680
Sebastian, I'm on the edge of the biggest deal of my life.

385
00:17:28,680 --> 00:17:31,486
 30 grand is a lot of money, hard to come up with.

386
00:17:31,486 --> 00:17:33,628
 Hey, here, I've got money.

387
00:17:37,300 --> 00:17:39,260
 This ain't even close to 30 grand.

388
00:17:39,260 --> 00:17:40,160
 That was a set up.

389
00:17:40,160 --> 00:17:41,445
You suckered me on that bet.

390
00:17:41,445 --> 00:17:42,560
 A bet's a bet.

391
00:17:42,560 --> 00:17:46,196
 Yeah, you sure act tough for a midget, Stubbs.

392
00:17:46,196 --> 00:17:47,096
Ooh!

393
00:17:47,096 --> 00:17:48,088
 No!

394
00:17:48,088 --> 00:17:49,080
Oh!

395
00:17:49,080 --> 00:17:50,164
[GRUNTING]

396
00:17:50,164 --> 00:17:51,064
Oh!

397
00:17:51,064 --> 00:17:52,148
Ah!

398
00:17:52,148 --> 00:17:53,048
Stop it!

399
00:17:56,540 --> 00:17:58,155
 Tomorrow at 6:00, Walter.

400
00:17:58,155 --> 00:18:01,782
I'm not waiting a couple days for a scum bucket like you.

401
00:18:01,782 --> 00:18:03,262
It's been a real pleasure, ma'am.

402
00:18:03,262 --> 00:18:05,672
[DOOR OPENS]

403
00:18:05,672 --> 00:18:08,082
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

404
00:18:10,492 --> 00:18:11,520
 Oh, dear god.

405
00:18:18,372 --> 00:18:19,464
[GRUNT]

406
00:18:19,464 --> 00:18:20,364
 Wait.

407
00:18:24,846 --> 00:18:28,332
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

408
00:18:43,272 --> 00:18:46,260
[CAR DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

409
00:18:46,260 --> 00:18:48,750
[CAR ENGINE STARTS]

410
00:18:52,734 --> 00:18:56,220
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

411
00:19:06,680 --> 00:19:10,688
 If I help you, will you promise to let me go?

412
00:19:10,688 --> 00:19:13,080
 Yes, ma'am.

413
00:19:13,080 --> 00:19:14,288
I cross my heart.

414
00:19:22,360 --> 00:19:26,030
 Ooh, I think your nose might be broken.

415
00:19:26,030 --> 00:19:29,546
Is there any trouble you aren't in?

416
00:19:29,546 --> 00:19:32,480
 Hm.

417
00:19:32,480 --> 00:19:33,950
Mm-mm.

418
00:19:33,950 --> 00:19:37,210
You have hands like a lady I knew once.

419
00:19:37,210 --> 00:19:38,720
You aren't a healer, are you?

420
00:19:38,720 --> 00:19:39,620
 Who, me?

421
00:19:42,230 --> 00:19:44,970
 This lady was a healer.

422
00:19:44,970 --> 00:19:47,600
I had this bad shoulder, chronic bad shoulder.

423
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:50,840
And she just lay hands on it.

424
00:19:50,840 --> 00:19:52,630
And the pain would vanish right into thin air.

425
00:19:55,270 --> 00:19:57,020
Any time I had a pain anywhere in my body,

426
00:19:57,020 --> 00:19:59,900
she just laid then hands on it.

427
00:20:04,220 --> 00:20:06,415
I miss that girl.

428
00:20:06,415 --> 00:20:07,315
 What happened?

429
00:20:10,050 --> 00:20:11,285
 I asked her to heal my hernia.

430
00:20:14,560 --> 00:20:15,742
I got to go to the bathroom.

431
00:20:15,742 --> 00:20:16,642
Ah!

432
00:20:30,530 --> 00:20:33,506
[TOILET FLUSHES]

433
00:20:53,250 --> 00:20:54,150
Happy birthday, honey.

434
00:20:59,679 --> 00:21:02,673
[SCRAPING SOUND]

435
00:21:24,130 --> 00:21:26,890
 So this is what a life of crime's like.

436
00:21:26,890 --> 00:21:28,000
 Don't bug me.

437
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:29,829
 Why are you doing that? The dye is indelible.

438
00:21:29,829 --> 00:21:30,940
 I said don't bug me.

439
00:21:30,940 --> 00:21:33,780
There's a way to do it.

440
00:21:33,780 --> 00:21:35,470
Brought in your groceries--

441
00:21:35,470 --> 00:21:38,040
peanut butter, Cap'n Crunch, seaweed,

442
00:21:38,040 --> 00:21:41,080
burdock root, and 15 packages of thawed out broccoli.

443
00:21:41,080 --> 00:21:44,560
You people in a cult or something?

444
00:21:44,560 --> 00:21:47,910
 Something happened in the grocery store.

445
00:21:47,910 --> 00:21:50,380
I think I had sort of a breakdown.

446
00:21:50,380 --> 00:21:51,760
 Is it over already?

447
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:52,660
 I guess.

448
00:21:52,660 --> 00:21:54,400
 Some breakdown.

449
00:21:54,400 --> 00:21:56,590
 My life has been like that.

450
00:21:56,590 --> 00:21:57,760
Every once in awhile something big

451
00:21:57,760 --> 00:21:59,840
happens, like having a baby.

452
00:21:59,840 --> 00:22:02,450
Then I just get back to business.

453
00:22:02,450 --> 00:22:05,908
I married a man who's very business like.

454
00:22:05,908 --> 00:22:08,237
[SIGHS] I guess I better go.

455
00:22:08,237 --> 00:22:09,370
WALTER: Grab yourself some coffee.

456
00:22:09,370 --> 00:22:10,790
It's on the stove. - No.

457
00:22:10,790 --> 00:22:12,500
I know they're worried about me.

458
00:22:12,500 --> 00:22:13,400
 Well, relax.

459
00:22:14,810 --> 00:22:16,310
BUNNY: What are you gonna do about those men?

460
00:22:16,310 --> 00:22:18,470
 Well, I'll worry about those men when the time comes.

461
00:22:18,470 --> 00:22:19,380
 When the time comes?

462
00:22:19,380 --> 00:22:20,650
That's only a few hours away.

463
00:22:20,650 --> 00:22:21,550
 Uh-uh, honey.

464
00:22:21,550 --> 00:22:22,477
It's 10 hours away.

465
00:22:22,477 --> 00:22:24,410
And I'm not going to get an ulcer worrying about something

466
00:22:24,410 --> 00:22:26,000
10 hours from now.

467
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:27,851
 Did you rob that bank to pay them?

468
00:22:27,851 --> 00:22:29,150
 Why don't you mind your own business?

469
00:22:30,664 --> 00:22:32,330
BUNNY: I would take then seriously, if I were you.

470
00:22:32,330 --> 00:22:33,854
They almost broke your nose already.

471
00:22:33,854 --> 00:22:34,754
 Wait a minute.

472
00:22:34,754 --> 00:22:35,654
Wait a minute.

473
00:22:35,654 --> 00:22:36,800
Are you my mother?

474
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:38,140
You think you have to take care of me?

475
00:22:38,140 --> 00:22:40,610
 You're not taking very good care of yourself.

476
00:22:40,610 --> 00:22:42,860
 [SCOFFS]

477
00:22:42,860 --> 00:22:43,960
 I'm talking too much.

478
00:22:43,960 --> 00:22:45,060
I got to go, Walter.

479
00:22:45,060 --> 00:22:47,890
 [INAUDIBLE],, sit down, and maybe you try scrubbing.

480
00:22:47,890 --> 00:22:49,350
Try some bleach or something.

481
00:22:49,350 --> 00:22:50,810
 I really don't want to.

482
00:22:50,810 --> 00:22:52,280
 Look, look, look.

483
00:22:52,280 --> 00:22:54,570
I appreciate you coming back and fixing me up.

484
00:22:54,570 --> 00:22:56,878
I'll never forget it.

485
00:22:56,878 --> 00:22:59,500
But, um, don't ever trust me again.

486
00:23:02,128 --> 00:23:03,990
I can't let you go.

487
00:23:03,990 --> 00:23:06,190
They'll get the story out of you for sure.

488
00:23:06,190 --> 00:23:09,170
- You are such a liar! - I always was.

489
00:23:11,834 --> 00:23:15,450
Walkin' out of here ain't gonna be as easy as you think.

490
00:23:15,450 --> 00:23:16,350
BUNNY: [GASPS]

491
00:23:16,350 --> 00:23:17,820
WALTER: Stubbs's been there all night.

492
00:23:17,820 --> 00:23:19,750
But Walter Sharphorn's got a plan.

493
00:23:19,750 --> 00:23:21,726
[BIRDSONG]

494
00:23:21,726 --> 00:23:25,184
[COUNTRY MUSIC PLAYING]

495
00:23:25,184 --> 00:23:26,810
 [SIGHS] This isn't gonna fool anybody.

496
00:23:26,810 --> 00:23:30,372
 It just has to get us to the car.

497
00:23:30,372 --> 00:23:32,240
Oh, I didn't realize there was that much woman

498
00:23:32,240 --> 00:23:34,680
under that sweatsuit.

499
00:23:34,680 --> 00:23:35,900
 Cheap and tacky.

500
00:23:35,900 --> 00:23:37,520
 Now, no need insulting my old girlfriend.

501
00:23:37,520 --> 00:23:38,530
I liked her taste.

502
00:23:38,530 --> 00:23:39,430
 It suits you.

503
00:23:39,430 --> 00:23:40,762
 It suits you too, honey.

504
00:23:43,502 --> 00:23:44,458
You coming?

505
00:23:51,077 --> 00:23:51,977
Come on.

506
00:23:56,450 --> 00:23:57,941
All right.

507
00:23:57,941 --> 00:23:58,935
Sell it, honey.

508
00:24:03,905 --> 00:24:05,987
[BIRDSONG]

509
00:24:05,987 --> 00:24:06,887
[DOG BARKING]

510
00:24:06,887 --> 00:24:08,378
Good dog. Good dog.

511
00:24:08,378 --> 00:24:09,372
Good dog.

512
00:24:09,372 --> 00:24:12,354
[BARKING]

513
00:24:18,815 --> 00:24:19,809
Follow me.

514
00:24:23,288 --> 00:24:25,276
[GATE SQUEAKS]

515
00:24:25,276 --> 00:24:26,861
Leave the damn gate!

516
00:24:26,861 --> 00:24:27,761
Come on.

517
00:24:54,102 --> 00:24:55,710
 (WHISPERS) You're supposed to be a woman.

518
00:24:55,710 --> 00:24:56,610
 Well, I forgot.

519
00:25:03,790 --> 00:25:04,780
[INAUDIBLE]

520
00:25:07,750 --> 00:25:08,740
[CAR ENGINE STARTS]

521
00:25:08,740 --> 00:25:09,730
Nice and easy.

522
00:25:18,930 --> 00:25:20,360
 I don't believe it.

523
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:21,962
 They don't expect imagination, honey.

524
00:25:21,962 --> 00:25:24,852
[LAUGHS]

525
00:25:32,615 --> 00:25:34,640
 How come I drive all the time?

526
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:36,020
 I don't have a license.

527
00:25:36,020 --> 00:25:36,920
Ah.

528
00:25:36,920 --> 00:25:43,880
Anyway, [CHUCKLES] I always had bad luck driving cars.

529
00:25:43,880 --> 00:25:45,878
 I'm not surprised.

530
00:25:45,878 --> 00:25:48,120
 [CHUCKLES] Want to hear something funny?

531
00:25:48,120 --> 00:25:50,570
I have a kid who's 18.

532
00:25:50,570 --> 00:25:52,400
And the only way he can get insurance on this car

533
00:25:52,400 --> 00:25:54,007
is to promise that I don't drive it.

534
00:25:54,007 --> 00:25:55,170
[CHUCKLES]

535
00:25:55,170 --> 00:25:56,570
 You're married?

536
00:25:56,570 --> 00:25:58,060
Can hardly believe it.

537
00:25:58,060 --> 00:25:59,040
 Well, not anymore.

538
00:25:59,040 --> 00:26:01,200
Sal threw me out a long time ago.

539
00:26:01,200 --> 00:26:03,066
But I still see my kid every now and again.

540
00:26:03,066 --> 00:26:06,350
He's a-- he's real different from me.

541
00:26:06,350 --> 00:26:09,610
[CHUCKLES] We used to be thick as thieves.

542
00:26:09,610 --> 00:26:10,565
But I don't know.

543
00:26:10,565 --> 00:26:14,620
If you don't spend time with them, then get away from you.

544
00:26:14,620 --> 00:26:17,600
 Happens even when you do.

545
00:26:17,600 --> 00:26:18,950
 Hm.

546
00:26:18,950 --> 00:26:21,071
 I'm hungry.

547
00:26:21,071 --> 00:26:23,556
 Yeah.

548
00:26:23,556 --> 00:26:26,970
Oh, I brought your flute.

549
00:26:26,970 --> 00:26:28,284
 That flute means a lot to me.

550
00:26:28,284 --> 00:26:29,736
 I figured that.

551
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:33,890
Here we are.

552
00:26:33,890 --> 00:26:35,220
What do you want, a burger? BUNNY: OK.

553
00:26:35,220 --> 00:26:36,120
WALTER: All right.

554
00:26:36,120 --> 00:26:38,050
Pull way back in the back lot.

555
00:26:38,050 --> 00:26:38,970
BUNNY: Why?

556
00:26:38,970 --> 00:26:40,436
WALTER: Because I don't trust you in public.

557
00:26:40,436 --> 00:26:43,060
That's why.

558
00:26:43,060 --> 00:26:45,900
All right, you slide over here on this side.

559
00:26:45,900 --> 00:26:47,180
 Why?

560
00:26:47,180 --> 00:26:48,760
 Just do it, would Ya you sure as hell

561
00:26:48,760 --> 00:26:50,770
were more agreeable yesterday.

562
00:26:50,770 --> 00:26:51,800
 I was scared yesterday.

563
00:26:51,800 --> 00:26:54,316
 Oh, you're not scared anymore?

564
00:26:54,316 --> 00:26:55,782
 What are you doing?

565
00:26:55,782 --> 00:26:56,706
Damn it.

566
00:26:56,706 --> 00:26:58,495
I will scream my head off!

567
00:26:58,495 --> 00:27:00,565
WALTER: You do, and you won't need it.

568
00:27:00,565 --> 00:27:01,465
BUNNY: Stop it!

569
00:27:01,465 --> 00:27:02,455
[INAUDIBLE] me.

570
00:27:02,455 --> 00:27:08,890
[SCREAMS]

571
00:27:08,890 --> 00:27:11,860
[TIRES SQUEALING]

572
00:27:11,860 --> 00:27:15,325
[BUNNY SCREAMS]

573
00:27:18,295 --> 00:27:19,285
[TIRES SQUEALING]

574
00:27:19,285 --> 00:27:22,750
 I [INAUDIBLE] picked a crazy woman.

575
00:27:22,750 --> 00:27:25,720
 [INAUDIBLE] get off.

576
00:27:25,720 --> 00:27:27,205
[SCREAMS]

577
00:27:27,205 --> 00:27:30,175
 [LAUGHS] I should have tied it around your neck.

578
00:27:38,640 --> 00:27:39,620
No funny business, OK?

579
00:27:39,620 --> 00:27:40,520
 OK.

580
00:27:48,150 --> 00:27:49,100
 Hey, how you doing?

581
00:27:49,100 --> 00:27:51,758
A couple coffees and, uh, two of those jelly rolls, please.

582
00:27:56,540 --> 00:27:57,970
- That'll be $1.65. - Great.

583
00:27:57,970 --> 00:27:59,470
Just take it out of that and keep the change.

584
00:28:00,685 --> 00:28:02,030
WAITRESS: Thank you. - Mm-hm.

585
00:28:02,030 --> 00:28:04,060
 What'd you do that for? We have to save money.

586
00:28:04,060 --> 00:28:05,470
 I've always been a big tipper.

587
00:28:05,470 --> 00:28:07,722
Now shut up and eat your jelly roll.

588
00:28:07,722 --> 00:28:13,650
[COUNTRY MUSIC PLAYING]

589
00:28:13,650 --> 00:28:15,132
 [INAUDIBLE].

590
00:28:20,072 --> 00:28:21,554
 Come on, let's go.

591
00:28:27,976 --> 00:28:29,200
Hi, number 42.

592
00:28:29,200 --> 00:28:30,144
Backseat will be fine.

593
00:28:30,144 --> 00:28:31,560
 What are you doing?

594
00:28:34,354 --> 00:28:35,420
You're stealing those groceries?

595
00:28:35,420 --> 00:28:36,320
 Shh.

596
00:28:37,670 --> 00:28:38,570
Great.

597
00:28:38,570 --> 00:28:39,606
Thank you.

598
00:28:44,470 --> 00:28:45,687
Pretty slick one.

599
00:28:45,687 --> 00:28:46,820
 What's that poor woman gonna do?

600
00:28:46,820 --> 00:28:47,960
 Oh, the store will make good.

601
00:28:47,960 --> 00:28:48,860
 How could you do that?

602
00:28:48,860 --> 00:28:49,850
 See what we got.

603
00:28:49,850 --> 00:28:51,649
- [SCOFFS] - Come on, Bunny.

604
00:28:51,649 --> 00:28:52,720
It's my worry not yours.

605
00:28:52,720 --> 00:28:53,620
Come on.

606
00:28:59,210 --> 00:29:01,080
 That woman's got a baby at home.

607
00:29:01,080 --> 00:29:03,500
Now she's got to shop all over again.

608
00:29:03,500 --> 00:29:04,590
You are some crook.

609
00:29:09,027 --> 00:29:11,824
Mm-mm, blueberry buckle, want a bite?

610
00:29:11,824 --> 00:29:13,390
WALTER: You sure there isn't any bread in there

611
00:29:13,390 --> 00:29:14,685
to make a sandwich?

612
00:29:14,685 --> 00:29:15,646
 No.

613
00:29:15,646 --> 00:29:18,325
I gotta go to the bathroom.

614
00:29:18,325 --> 00:29:19,810
 [INAUDIBLE].

615
00:29:19,810 --> 00:29:22,030
Well, why didn't you ask me when we were in the market?

616
00:29:22,030 --> 00:29:23,440
[BIRDSONG]

617
00:29:23,440 --> 00:29:28,140
 [CHUCKLES]

618
00:29:28,140 --> 00:29:30,720
 Now what your trouble?

619
00:29:30,720 --> 00:29:36,670
 Walter, do you think you're some kind of guardian angel?

620
00:29:36,670 --> 00:29:38,770
 You all right?

621
00:29:38,770 --> 00:29:41,650
 I think I am.

622
00:29:41,650 --> 00:29:45,130
I think I'm better than I've been in a long time.

623
00:29:45,130 --> 00:29:48,070
 Good. Stop talking rubbish.

624
00:29:50,830 --> 00:29:52,420
 You don't understand, Walter.

625
00:29:52,420 --> 00:29:54,220
Yesterday I stood there in the produce aisle

626
00:29:54,220 --> 00:29:56,080
just wishing I could disappear.

627
00:29:56,080 --> 00:29:57,580
And look what happened.

628
00:29:57,580 --> 00:29:58,930
I did.

629
00:29:58,930 --> 00:30:01,000
You did it for me, Walter.

630
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:05,030
You poor guy, you have to be responsible for me.

631
00:30:05,030 --> 00:30:08,710
I don't have to do one single thing except drive and sit.

632
00:30:08,710 --> 00:30:12,460
You have to feed me, find me a bathroom when I want one,

633
00:30:12,460 --> 00:30:16,510
worry about me, money, and the police

634
00:30:16,510 --> 00:30:18,520
and those rough characters, those crooks.

635
00:30:18,520 --> 00:30:21,050
Day and night, worry, worry, worry.

636
00:30:21,050 --> 00:30:22,630
Well, I know what it's like, Walter.

637
00:30:22,630 --> 00:30:24,680
And you can have it.

638
00:30:24,680 --> 00:30:27,550
 Yeah, well, that's the difference between you

639
00:30:27,550 --> 00:30:28,450
and me, Bunny.

640
00:30:28,450 --> 00:30:29,450
You let it get to you.

641
00:30:29,450 --> 00:30:31,370
If you had my problems, you'd be a basket case.

642
00:30:31,370 --> 00:30:33,850
Look at me, calm as a clam.

643
00:30:33,850 --> 00:30:35,470
 I don't believe you one bit.

644
00:30:35,470 --> 00:30:38,710
Where you gonna find $30,000?

645
00:30:38,710 --> 00:30:40,180
 That's for me to know and you to find out.

646
00:30:40,180 --> 00:30:41,620
BUNNY: Mm.

647
00:30:41,620 --> 00:30:44,020
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

648
00:30:46,600 --> 00:30:47,500
 Break it down.

649
00:30:50,657 --> 00:30:52,390
Walter!

650
00:30:52,390 --> 00:30:53,318
Yoo-hoo, Walter!

651
00:30:53,318 --> 00:30:54,990
We're looking for you.

652
00:30:54,990 --> 00:30:58,734
Got something for you.

653
00:30:58,734 --> 00:31:03,090
 Sebastian, look at that.

654
00:31:03,090 --> 00:31:04,600
He's killed himself.

655
00:31:04,600 --> 00:31:06,490
 If he killed himself, where is he?

656
00:31:06,490 --> 00:31:07,680
He's gone, you idiot.

657
00:31:11,140 --> 00:31:12,610
 I've been here since last night.

658
00:31:12,610 --> 00:31:14,190
Nobody went out.

659
00:31:14,190 --> 00:31:16,290
The only people I saw all day was two women come out

660
00:31:16,290 --> 00:31:17,980
of the house across the street.

661
00:31:17,980 --> 00:31:20,680
I'm telling you his car's still in the garage, you watch.

662
00:31:24,180 --> 00:31:25,080
Woo-wee!

663
00:31:25,080 --> 00:31:27,700
Where'd he get a car like that?

664
00:31:27,700 --> 00:31:30,390
 Jeffrey's life has been turned into a living hell by her.

665
00:31:30,390 --> 00:31:34,284
She treats him like a dog [INAUDIBLE]..

666
00:31:34,284 --> 00:31:35,850
Who would buy this crap?

667
00:31:35,850 --> 00:31:39,535
Specialist says sex may cause cancer.

668
00:31:39,535 --> 00:31:40,435
 I'm tired.

669
00:31:40,435 --> 00:31:42,270
Where we going?

670
00:31:42,270 --> 00:31:43,955
 Just make a left at the crossroads

671
00:31:43,955 --> 00:31:46,870
at the far end of town.

672
00:31:46,870 --> 00:31:48,400
 I love the way you always pretend like you

673
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:50,650
know what you're doing.

674
00:31:50,650 --> 00:31:53,110
 Want to get dumped in the ditch?

675
00:31:53,110 --> 00:31:55,140
 You don't scare me anymore, Walter.

676
00:31:55,140 --> 00:31:57,980
I bet that gun of yours isn't even loaded.

677
00:31:57,980 --> 00:31:59,810
 You're getting awful cocky in your old age, Bunny.

678
00:31:59,810 --> 00:32:01,900
 How come you never pulled it on those crooks?

679
00:32:01,900 --> 00:32:03,240
I bet because there's nothing in it.

680
00:32:03,240 --> 00:32:04,900
That's why.

681
00:32:04,900 --> 00:32:05,810
 Crooks is a dumb word.

682
00:32:05,810 --> 00:32:07,850
Don't say it anymore, all right?

683
00:32:07,850 --> 00:32:10,510
If I had pulled it on them, we'd probably both be dead by now.

684
00:32:10,510 --> 00:32:11,410
 Bull.

685
00:32:15,346 --> 00:32:16,330
[GUN CLICKS]

686
00:32:16,330 --> 00:32:17,314
[GUNSHOT]

687
00:32:17,314 --> 00:32:23,218
 [SCREAMS]

688
00:32:23,218 --> 00:32:26,170
[RUMBLING SOUND]

689
00:32:35,030 --> 00:32:36,430
 See what you made me do?

690
00:32:36,430 --> 00:32:37,810
 You are weird, Walter.

691
00:32:37,810 --> 00:32:39,244
You really are.

692
00:32:42,650 --> 00:32:43,550
 Woo-wee!

693
00:32:43,550 --> 00:32:44,846
This is my kind of vehicle.

694
00:32:44,846 --> 00:32:45,746
Listen to that engine.

695
00:32:45,746 --> 00:32:48,580
I don't trust foreign cars.

696
00:32:48,580 --> 00:32:49,980
 Stubb, you're a redneck.

697
00:32:49,980 --> 00:32:50,920
You're low class.

698
00:32:50,920 --> 00:32:52,930
A guy like you could never appreciate a car like this.

699
00:32:52,930 --> 00:32:55,930
 I'll take an American car over this any day.

700
00:32:55,930 --> 00:32:56,830
I live in this country.

701
00:32:56,830 --> 00:32:57,750
I buy American.

702
00:32:57,750 --> 00:32:59,230
 Yeah, right.

703
00:32:59,230 --> 00:33:01,155
Buy American, you steal foreign.

704
00:33:01,155 --> 00:33:03,430
[SIREN]

705
00:33:03,430 --> 00:33:05,740
 Well, don't look at me.

706
00:33:05,740 --> 00:33:07,402
I'm driving good.

707
00:33:07,402 --> 00:33:08,800
 [SIGHS] This is car is hot.

708
00:33:08,800 --> 00:33:09,900
That slime, Walter.

709
00:33:09,900 --> 00:33:10,800
Pull it over.

710
00:33:19,900 --> 00:33:21,180
 What do we say?

711
00:33:21,180 --> 00:33:22,750
SEBASTIAN: I'll do the talking.

712
00:33:22,750 --> 00:33:23,790
Shut up and play dumb.

713
00:33:23,790 --> 00:33:24,690
Just act natural.

714
00:33:24,690 --> 00:33:26,510
 All right, everybody out of the car, hands on--

715
00:33:26,510 --> 00:33:27,430
 Oh, man.

716
00:33:27,430 --> 00:33:28,330
OFFICER: What the hell.

717
00:33:28,330 --> 00:33:29,664
Sebastian, what are you doing with this?

718
00:33:29,664 --> 00:33:31,850
 Hey, Marty. How do you like my new wheels?

719
00:33:31,850 --> 00:33:32,750
 You're crazy.

720
00:33:32,750 --> 00:33:34,220
There's a missing person's report

721
00:33:34,220 --> 00:33:35,580
out on a woman who owns this.

722
00:33:35,580 --> 00:33:36,640
 I'll kill him.

723
00:33:36,640 --> 00:33:38,070
Look, Marty, we had nothing to do with it.

724
00:33:38,070 --> 00:33:39,825
We took this as collateral on a debt.

725
00:33:39,825 --> 00:33:41,070
 Yeah, no keys-- I see.

726
00:33:41,070 --> 00:33:42,030
You took it.

727
00:33:42,030 --> 00:33:43,456
 Jerk's name is Walter Sharphorn.

728
00:33:43,456 --> 00:33:44,355
He had a woman with him.

729
00:33:44,355 --> 00:33:45,570
He just disappeared without paying

730
00:33:45,570 --> 00:33:48,300
me a large bundle of cash, and I'm very unhappy with the man.

731
00:33:48,300 --> 00:33:49,200
 Is this her?

732
00:33:51,937 --> 00:33:53,270
 She looked a little rattier than that,

733
00:33:53,270 --> 00:33:54,650
but yeah, that's the one.

734
00:33:54,650 --> 00:33:56,251
 Well, maybe we have a kidnapping on her hands.

735
00:33:56,251 --> 00:33:58,610
 Walter? [SCOFFS] You got to be kidding.

736
00:33:58,610 --> 00:33:59,670
She acted like his girlfriend.

737
00:33:59,670 --> 00:34:00,570
OFFICER: Hm.

738
00:34:00,570 --> 00:34:02,370
 Can we go now, Marty?

739
00:34:02,370 --> 00:34:04,241
 Yeah, on foot.

740
00:34:04,241 --> 00:34:05,640
Hey, you guys, just leave this right here.

741
00:34:05,640 --> 00:34:07,250
I'll do you a big favor.

742
00:34:07,250 --> 00:34:08,847
I'll tell 'em I found it abandoned.

743
00:34:08,847 --> 00:34:10,380
Just return the favor at the end of the month.

744
00:34:16,974 --> 00:34:19,179
 [SIGHS] Maybe he did kidnap her.

745
00:34:19,179 --> 00:34:20,540
Maybe that's what he was talking about.

746
00:34:20,540 --> 00:34:22,550
 Well, why didn't you tell Marty?

747
00:34:22,550 --> 00:34:23,900
 If the cops catch him before we do,

748
00:34:23,900 --> 00:34:25,580
we'll never get a cent, peanut head.

749
00:34:29,470 --> 00:34:30,400
BUNNY: Where are we now?

750
00:34:30,400 --> 00:34:31,690
We're lost, aren't we?

751
00:34:31,690 --> 00:34:32,800
I'm freezing.

752
00:34:32,800 --> 00:34:34,299
WALTER: Just quit complaining, would ya?

753
00:34:34,299 --> 00:34:35,199
Trust me.

754
00:34:35,199 --> 00:34:37,065
BUNNY: You've never done one thing to make me trust you.

755
00:34:37,065 --> 00:34:38,670
WALTER: Well, that's a fine thing to say.

756
00:34:38,670 --> 00:34:42,190
You're about to meet my mother.

757
00:34:42,190 --> 00:34:44,377
 First you kidnap me, and then you

758
00:34:44,377 --> 00:34:45,310
take me to meet your mother.

759
00:34:45,310 --> 00:34:46,443
 I wish you'd stop saying kidnap.

760
00:34:46,443 --> 00:34:47,510
It gives me the willies.

761
00:34:47,510 --> 00:34:48,969
 I don't understand you, Walter.

762
00:34:48,969 --> 00:34:50,076
[KNOCKS ON DOOR]

763
00:34:50,076 --> 00:34:51,590
 I didn't kidnap you, Bunny.

764
00:34:51,590 --> 00:34:53,714
I got you out of the house, didn't I?

765
00:34:53,714 --> 00:34:55,839
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

766
00:34:55,839 --> 00:34:56,739
 What's your mother like?

767
00:34:56,739 --> 00:34:58,940
 [SIGHS] Nobody you ever met.

768
00:35:03,250 --> 00:35:04,315
 Is it Christmas already?

769
00:35:07,360 --> 00:35:08,986
You aren't married again, are ya?

770
00:35:08,986 --> 00:35:10,120
 Mm-mm.

771
00:35:10,120 --> 00:35:11,020
 Thank god.

772
00:35:11,020 --> 00:35:13,220
That's a blessing.

773
00:35:13,220 --> 00:35:14,600
He's the dumbest one of my kids.

774
00:35:14,600 --> 00:35:17,131
 Yeah, I take after my ma.

775
00:35:17,131 --> 00:35:18,195
[CHUCKLES]

776
00:35:18,195 --> 00:35:19,095
 [LAUGHS]

777
00:35:19,095 --> 00:35:20,394
 Come here.

778
00:35:20,394 --> 00:35:21,560
 Damn, if you don't make me laugh.

779
00:35:21,560 --> 00:35:23,360
[LAUGHS]

780
00:35:23,360 --> 00:35:26,750
 Rowena Sharphorn, meet Bunny Brown.

781
00:35:26,750 --> 00:35:31,570
 Bunny Brown, what a cute little name.

782
00:35:31,570 --> 00:35:34,670
Well, come on in.

783
00:35:34,670 --> 00:35:36,280
I'm skinning a bobcat.

784
00:35:36,280 --> 00:35:40,400
You had your dinner yet

785
00:35:40,400 --> 00:35:41,630
 Rowena's a taxidermist.

786
00:35:47,330 --> 00:35:51,140
 Come on in and make yourself at home.

787
00:35:51,140 --> 00:35:52,730
[CAT SCREECHES]

788
00:35:52,730 --> 00:35:53,630
 Ah!

789
00:35:53,630 --> 00:35:54,770
 Don't mind the cats.

790
00:35:54,770 --> 00:35:57,920
Only two mean ones, and they hide from company.

791
00:35:57,920 --> 00:36:00,260
They earn their bed and board, cats do.

792
00:36:00,260 --> 00:36:01,940
Keep the dust down.

793
00:36:01,940 --> 00:36:05,270
 I never thought about that.

794
00:36:05,270 --> 00:36:08,210
 You, uh, like my son, is that right?

795
00:36:08,210 --> 00:36:09,110
 Well--

796
00:36:09,110 --> 00:36:10,490
 Don't be so nosy, Rowena.

797
00:36:10,490 --> 00:36:12,130
We just met yesterday.

798
00:36:12,130 --> 00:36:14,330
And we thought we'd come by and visit my sweet little mother

799
00:36:14,330 --> 00:36:15,230
for a couple of days.

800
00:36:15,230 --> 00:36:17,030
 He's got a real good sense of humor,

801
00:36:17,030 --> 00:36:21,740
Walter has, but no more common sense than a stud monkey.

802
00:36:21,740 --> 00:36:24,790
I never met a man had both, did you?

803
00:36:24,790 --> 00:36:28,540
 I've never thought about that either.

804
00:36:28,540 --> 00:36:29,801
 Ah.

805
00:36:29,801 --> 00:36:30,800
Not much of a thinker, is she?

806
00:36:34,130 --> 00:36:36,640
Takes a lot of patience, that kind of work.

807
00:36:36,640 --> 00:36:38,030
But it keeps me occupied.

808
00:36:38,030 --> 00:36:42,560
It's relaxing, sort of like knitting, know what I mean?

809
00:36:42,560 --> 00:36:44,405
Walter, don't even think of touching that bird.

810
00:36:44,405 --> 00:36:46,250
I worked on that thing for two months.

811
00:36:46,250 --> 00:36:49,220
It's the best ring-neck I ever did.

812
00:36:49,220 --> 00:36:52,580
Now, let's see, I got some steaks in this freezer.

813
00:36:52,580 --> 00:36:54,708
What do you say we grill 'em up?

814
00:36:54,708 --> 00:36:56,200
ARCHIE (ON TV) --the midnight insanity sale!

815
00:36:56,200 --> 00:36:59,530
That's right, folks, we're open till midnight every day

